## Why This Is Asked
3D Morton codes enable fast spatial indexing in grid-like domains; a branchless, fixed-bit spreading approach scales predictably. 

## Key Concepts
- Morton codes for 3D require interleaving bits from three coordinates.
- Bit spreading (dilating) inserts two zero bits between each original bit; a fixed sequence of masks/shifts yields a branchless implementation.
- BigInt vs. Number in JavaScript: use BigInt for 64-bit results if implementing in JS; otherwise 64-bit types in C/C++ handle it natively.

## Code Example
```javascript
function part1by2(n) {
  let x = BigInt(n) & 0x1fffffn; // 21 bits
  x = (x | (x << 32n)) & 0x1f00000000ffffn;
  x = (x | (x << 16n)) & 0x1f0000ff0000ffn;
  x = (x | (x << 8n)) & 0x100f00f00f00f00fn;
  x = (x | (x << 4n)) & 0x10c30c30c30c30c3n;
  x = (x | (x << 2n)) & 0x1249249249249249n;
  return x;
}
function morton3D(x, y, z) {
  return part1by2(x) | (part1by2(y) << 1n) | (part1by2(z) << 2n);
}
```

